**who —** PHILIPS CD-i — an exereunesis sphere — the teardown

**what —** Philips pitched the CD-i not as a games console but as an interactive multimedia player for the living room — encyclopaedias, music, edutainment — built on a 68000-family CPU. It's best remembered, unfairly to its intent, for a clutch of dire Zelda and Mario games made under a licensing deal with Nintendo.

**where —** the teardown — a made machine, opened and explored  Framework inputs: the chips; the buses; the spec; the lore  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** Philips pitched the CD-i not as a games console but as an interactive multimedia player for the living room — encyclopaedias, music, edutainment — built on a 68000-family CPU. It's best remembered, unfairly to its intent, for a clutch of dire Zelda and Mario games made under a licensing deal with Nintendo.

